Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

The following warnings in `docker info` are now discarded,
because there is no action user can actually take.

On cgroup v1:
- "WARNING: No blkio weight support"
- "WARNING: No blkio weight_device support"

On cgroup v2:

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

Signed-off-by: Kazuyoshi Kato <katokazu@amazon.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dk-cpa-68/moby/commits/bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3"},{"sha":"c0c3e58bb2b3714683658d331a138b2d80a6e974","author":{"name":"Sebastiaan van Stijn","email":"2b34a3e3e055981c6c83bcd4f9afd06751b4ac0e@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #41909 from kzys/41794-sized-logger

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,
when a plugin is started the shim config is nil.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Skarlso/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/dk-cpa-68/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/MRS-OS/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Rachelmorrell/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4d4ad89634b9492a94e3b8e504cab8d9593b6b65","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add HloSharding WithMetadata helper function to create a HloSharding copy with a specified metadata.

[{"sha":"212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818","author":{"name":"Alisdair McDiarmid","email":"87d32f97664e6609e4bd0bde109443ba47829a78@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"cli: Fix state migration remote version check

Previously the state migration process was using the fallback strict
error check when migrating to or from a Terraform Cloud workspace. This
resulted in an error when running init if the local and remote Terraform
versions did not exactly match.

This was excessively strict. When migrating from a remote Terraform
Cloud workspace to local state, there is no need for a version check at
all, as we cannot break the Terraform Cloud workspace. When migrating
to Terraform Cloud, we should use the more forgiving check, rather than
the strict equality.

This commit fixes both of these cases accordingly, and allows migrating
state to and from Terraform Cloud remote workspaces without errors.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tokyo2006/terraform/commits/212a97c3bdf1cce82d1ca14b91e4f79c176a9818"},{"sha":"44daf76624c6445ff82d0634b1e00091b579db68","author":{"name":"James Bardin","email":"62973226c85cb5a1996aaed2ce372ac02dcad8b7@gmail.com"},"message":"remove InitProvisioner and close all at once

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"f48ae3edac6c0139a4e48c80432a6ddb54d2f4cc","author":{"name":"A. Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rcowsill/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

volumes/local: gofmt","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rcowsill/moby/commits/0456e058d2b60606d4374cd975c635dfe7673f17"},{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rcowsill/moby/commits/d5612a0ef8aa5c43f8345302e8d20b5fd25517b3"},{"sha":"72de07a8f2c78063cb6a2a63bfa9867652c9bb63","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,
when a plugin is started the shim config is nil.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/bergwolf/moby/commits/399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742"},{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

Signed-off-by: Akihiro Suda <akihiro.suda.cz@hco.ntt.co.jp>","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rcowsill/moby/commits/00225e220fb18283dcf9e4fa6625fad6746d8a50"},{"sha":"b865beba22aac576b95952fef97d4e775632c362","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"e0805010dd8083d2b1d03fddca6d3bb7d7654435@microsoft.com"},"message":"Merge pull request #41894 from AkihiroSuda/silence-dockerinfo","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/rcowsill/moby/commits/b865beba22aac576b95952fef97d4e775632c362"},{"sha":"42dba8c3f9a821c64864c49e60fff9b3ba3e86c5","author":{"name":"Rob Cowsill","email":"4ced00c28ea0046018d361ef4a0a1cf292775363@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Fix spurious error from "docker load"

"docker load" validates parent links by comparing image histories, and the
History struct has a time.Time member "Created". Time.UnmarshalJSON can read
RFC3339 timestamps with offset "+00:00", but t.MarshalJSON writes them with
offset "Z". Equivalent times in these two formats are not equal when compared
with the == operator.

This causes checkValidParent to incorrectly return false when the parent image
history contains times using offset "+00:00". In that case the history copied
to the child image will have been converted into "Z" form when marshaled out.

This patch adds an "Equal" method to History, which compares "Created" times
with t.Equal. This is used instead of reflect.DeepEqual in checkValidParent.

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/UofT-EcoSystem/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4f56ac2f1b8a2a717059801f7aef8b4c3a30a100","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46473 from advaitjain:makefile-param-co-processor

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/akram/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4d4ad89634b9492a94e3b8e504cab8d9593b6b65","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add HloSharding WithMetadata helper function to create a HloSharding copy with a specified metadata.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/phiberoptick/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tfl0pz/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4d4ad89634b9492a94e3b8e504cab8d9593b6b65","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add HloSharding WithMetadata helper function to create a HloSharding copy with a specified metadata.

Change ToLiteral() to have an asynchronous API that writes its output into a caller-provided buffer. Delete CopyToHostAsync() because it now serves no purpose.

Caching host transfers is a policy decision that PJRT should not be making on behalf of clients. Instead, clients can cache the transfer results if they want. The original motivation for the cache was the Python bindings; this change moves the cache into the Python bindings. This simplifies the PJRT API.

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/vdemeester/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/kaycoinsUSA/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/next-stack/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/JonathanSimon123/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,
when a plugin is started the shim config is nil.

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/Mu-L/moby/commits/399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742"},{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

[{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/normanheckscher/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4d4ad89634b9492a94e3b8e504cab8d9593b6b65","author":{"name":"Andy Ly","email":"ee92f4a5326670b7718293ef87adfe1573316ab0@google.com"},"message":"Add HloSharding WithMetadata helper function to create a HloSharding copy with a specified metadata.

[{"sha":"2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Add shim config for custom runtimes for plugins

This fixes a panic when an admin specifies a custom default runtime,

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/2903863a1d7313118255dc8cc0664cdfe3e6a379"},{"sha":"399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742","author":{"name":"Brian Goff","email":"dc73d0991b982a8303e713ef531a313af77e242a@gmail.com"},"message":"Fix builder inconsistent error on buggy platform

When pulling an image by platform, it is possible for the image's
configured platform to not match what was in the manifest list.
The image itself is buggy because either the manifest list is incorrect
or the image config is incorrect. In any case, this is preventing people
from upgrading because many times users do not have control over these
buggy images.

This was not a problem in 19.03 because we did not compare on platform
before. It just assumed if we had the image it was the one we wanted
regardless of platform, which has its own problems.

Example Dockerfile that has this problem:

```Dockerfile
FROM --platform=linux/arm64 k8s.gcr.io/build-image/debian-iptables:buster-v1.3.0
RUN echo hello
```

This fails the first time you try to build after it finishes pulling but
before performing the `RUN` command.
On the second attempt it works because the image is already there and
does not hit the code that errors out on platform mismatch (Actually it
ignores errors if an image is returned at all).

Must be run with the classic builder (DOCKER_BUILDKIT=0).

Signed-off-by: Brian Goff <cpuguy83@gmail.com>","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/meunice/moby/commits/399695305c67aae1010e6754f90f9078aa39e742"},{"sha":"bb11365e96a4f25fe20606b30cbfb79998fadff3","author":{"name":"Kazuyoshi Kato","email":"732288c132d39c7d9231a005036e5ecd0fff1d64@amazon.com"},"message":"Handle long log messages correctly on SizedLogger

Loggers that implement BufSize() (e.g. awslogs) uses the method to
tell Copier about the maximum log line length. However loggerWithCache
and RingBuffer hide the method by wrapping loggers.

As a result, Copier uses its default 16KB limit which breaks log
lines > 16kB even the destinations can handle that.

This change implements BufSize() on loggerWithCache and RingBuffer to
make sure these logger wrappes don't hide the method on the underlying
loggers.

Fixes #41794.

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```

[{"sha":"a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Remove support for TAGS from the TFLM Makefile.

This change started as a switch cmsis-nn and ethos-u to using
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR. However, supporting both
OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn and TAGS=cmsis-nn required a lot of
workarounds.

As a result, it was decided to also remove the deprecated TAGS
functionality.

This change also adds a new CO_PROCESSOR command line parameter to the
TFLM makefile.

specifying CO_PROCESSOR=<c> and OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=<o> will result in
the following:
 * tools/make/ext_libs/<o>.inc and tools/make/ext_libs/<c>.inc will be
   included from the Makefile
 * kernel sources will be specialized from both kernels/<o>.inc and
   kernels/<c>.inc (in that order).
 * the specialization order is important because it means that if the
   same kernel in implemented in both optimized_kernel_dir and
   the co_processor, then the co_processor implementation will be used.

Tested the following commands locally:

Build for cortex-m55 + reference kernels + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

Build for cortex-m55 + cmsis-nn kernels (as available) + ethos-u kernel:
```
make -f tensorflow/lite/micro/tools/make/Makefile -j8 TARGET=cortex_m_generic TARGET_ARCH=cortex-m55 OPTIMIZED_KERNEL_DIR=cmsis-nn CO_PROCESSOR=ethos-u microlite
```

See the discussion on
https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/pull/46352 for some more
context.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/tensorflow/tensorflow/commits/a23e5362670e3d9470369f9de56cba5343292209"},{"sha":"4f56ac2f1b8a2a717059801f7aef8b4c3a30a100","author":{"name":"TensorFlower Gardener","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Merge pull request #46473 from advaitjain:makefile-param-co-processor

Unique TensorFlower","email":"746aced590a184ef4169166e753f7c211e32e5fc@tensorflow.org"},"message":"Add checks to ensure all arguments have valid values during input canonicalization.

Before this update, the behavior of tf.function is not consistent with a "naked" function call:
```
>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func() missing 1 required positional argument: 'position_arg'

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
(<tf.Tensor: shape=(), dtype=string, numpy=b'Hello'>, None)
After the update:

>>> def func(position_arg, named_arg=None):
      return position_arg, named_arg

>>> tf_func = tf.function(func)

>>> tf_func(named_arg="Hello")
TypeError: func(position_arg, named_arg) missing 1 required argument: position_arg
```
